The real education President

Fourteen thousand dollars. That’s how much it costs
for an out—of-state student to attend the University of
Pittsburgh. Many students are then faced with the frus-
trations of ﬁlling out those seemingly endless fmancial-
aid forms in hopes of receiving loans, promissory notes
and grants. Most who sign those papers are unaware of
the consequences of non-repayment. Even if they are,
many are desperate for the moriey. By signing one’s
name to those f1nancial—aid forms, one practically signs
away any and all freedom from life without annual per-
centage. Loan defaults and late repayments raise the
cost of continuing aid, and all but limit the amount one
can receive in a given year. Even with the help of stu-
dent loans and grants, it’s all but impossible to avoid
impending debt after graduation.

However, with Clinton’s National Service proposal to
offset tuition costs, all is not lost. With his new initiative,
future college students can repay their debts by working
for minimum wage in various community fields, such as
law enforcement or student teaching.

“For each year of service, one or two years, partici-
pants in national—service programs will receive beneﬁts
that can be used toward past, present or future obliga-
tions," Clinton said at a recent speech in New Orleans.

It’s about time somebody tried to take some initiative
to start a national program to help students pay for col-
lege.

By 1994. 23,000 students are expected to participate in
many important. much-needed jobs. Teaching, environ-
mentalism, public safety, providing care to the elderly
and building shelters for the homeless are a few possi-
ble job fields being explored. Clinton ensures it will not
hamper presently employed people and their positions.
“Participants may not displace or duplicate the existing
workers”, said Director of National Service Eli Segal,

. who was appointed to oversee the operation.

Skeptics of the plan, however, argue that it is too cost-
ly and the risks are too great. Nonetheless the plan,
although a rough draft, encourages high hopes.
Although it may be difficult, it is not impossible to be
carried out in an efficient and effective manner. The
University of Pittsburgh, being a major institution,
should be at the forefront and be responsible for assist-
ing Clinton and his proposal as much as possible.

The benefits definitely outweigh the risks involved.
This program can begin to funnel students away from
otherwise mediocre jobs, allowing them to be produc-
tive and beneficial to their communities in exchange for
a repaid loan. Of course, specifics of the plan would
have to be worked out, and there are no guarantees.
But to fix the status quo, the students and administrators
must now make a serious effort to help change current
conditions and put Clinton’s proposal on paper.

   
     

