as the still picture: light. That’s exactly the
strength of Visions of Light: its ability to
illuminate the art of cinematography, the
art of light on film, at a level which
requires only a minimal amount of film lit~
eracy to appreciate and still maintains an
interest to the filmmaker or cinephile.

V1'sz'cms Q/‘Light is a tribute. In that spirit
it traces the unsung heroes of film, the
cinematographers, through clips of their
work from Birth of/1 Nation to the newest
generation of establ-ished filmmakers.
There is nothing new about this film’s
approach, a straight—forward, chronologi-
cal mix of film clips and stills of the early-
pioneer Hollywood legends mixed with
commentaries by the living generations of
cinematographers. A sense of the art of a
film’s director of photography emerges
mainly from these interviews. As each cin-
ematographer talks about the work of
peers and predecessors alike, the audi-
ence has the rare opportunity to both hear
and see, through the use of clips, how the
art of cinematography translates into the
images which we see on screen.

Those images have essentially become
part of the fabric of American culture. As
diverse as Gone With The Wind and
Apocalypse Now or the stylized cine—
matography of film noir and jaws may
seem, these images live on and a tribute
to their creators reveals an underexposed
side of our film culture as a whole. That
these images are compiled for us on the
big screen is really a privilege. Filmmakers
Arnold Glassman, Todd McCarthy and

‘Cinematographer Stanley Cortezis work in 1955’s The Night of the Hunter is

featured in Visions of Light, a tribute to the art of cinematography.

Stuart Samuels have managed in Visions
of Light to expose the art of some of
films most sacred and groundbreaking
images from their creators’ standpoint and
offer an accessible and entertaining tribute

to film itself.

Visions of Light: The Art of
Cinematography opens Friday, June 4
and runs until June 10 at the Playhouse.
